&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;electric field&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;always perpendicular&lt;/strong&gt; to the &lt;strong&gt;magnetic field&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;both fields&lt;/strong&gt; are &lt;strong&gt;directed at right-angles&lt;/strong&gt; to the &lt;strong&gt;direction of propagation&lt;/strong&gt; of the wave.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The wave propagates in the direction E &amp;times; B. Electromagnetic waves are a type of transverse wave.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/06/F1_J.K_Madhu_28.05.20_D15.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 435px; height: 190px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In electromagnetic waves &lt;strong&gt;the electric field is always perpendicular to the magnetic field&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;both field are directed at right &amp;ndash;angles&lt;/strong&gt; to the &lt;strong&gt;direction of propagation of the wave&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So option 4 is correct.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gauss&amp;rsquo;s law: &lt;/strong&gt;Gauss&amp;#39; law states that the electric flux through &lt;strong&gt;any closed surface&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;equal to the total charge inside the surface&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;divided by &amp;epsilon;&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;. Charges are the source and sinks of the electric field.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Biot savart law: &lt;/strong&gt;The Biot Savart Law states&amp;nbsp;that &lt;strong&gt;magnetic intensity (dB)&lt;/strong&gt; at a point A&lt;strong&gt; due to current I flowing&lt;/strong&gt; through &lt;strong&gt;a small element dl &lt;/strong&gt;is &lt;strong&gt;Directly &lt;/strong&gt;proportional to &lt;strong&gt;the current (I)&lt;/strong&gt;.
	&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type:circle;&quot;&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;It relates the magnetic field to the &lt;strong&gt;magnitude, direction, length, and proximity of the electric current&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Biot&amp;ndash;Savart law is consistent with both &lt;strong&gt;Ampere&amp;rsquo;s circuital law&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;Gauss&amp;rsquo;s theorem.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​Ampere&amp;#39;s law states&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;The magnetic field created by an electric current is proportional to the size of that electric current with a constant of proportionality equal to the permeability of free space&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/06/F1_J.K_Madhu_28.05.20_D13.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 184px; height: 194px;&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:.25in;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;magnetic field at the centre of the circular coil&lt;/strong&gt; is given by;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({\rm{B}} = \frac{{{{\rm{\mu }}_0}{\rm{I}}}}{{2{\rm{\pi R}}}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;Where B = strength of magnetic field, I = current, R = radius or distance.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Faraday&amp;#39;s law&lt;/strong&gt;: The &lt;strong&gt;rate of change&lt;/strong&gt; of &lt;strong&gt;magnetic flux&lt;/strong&gt; through a loop to the magnitude of the &lt;strong&gt;electromotive force&lt;/strong&gt; induced in the loop.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The relationship is&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({\rm{E}} = \frac{{{\rm{d}}\phi }}{{{\rm{dt}}}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;Where E = electromotive force, dϕ = flux changing, dt = time&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It relates the magnetic field to the &lt;strong&gt;magnitude, direction, length, and proximity of the electric current&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Biot&amp;ndash;Savart law is consistent with both &lt;strong&gt;Ampere&amp;rsquo;s circuital law&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;Gauss&amp;rsquo;s theorem.&lt;/strong&gt; So option 2 follows. Hence option 2 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Biot-Savart Law and Ampere&amp;#39;s law are related in their common function. Both laws can be sued to derive the magnetic field for various arrangements of current-carrying conductors. (Choosing which the law is the easiest will come with practice.)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Specific Heat Capacity&lt;/strong&gt;: Specific heat capacity is the &lt;strong&gt;energy required to increase&lt;/strong&gt; the temperature of the material of a certain mass&lt;strong&gt; by 1&amp;deg;C&lt;/strong&gt;.

	&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type:circle;&quot;&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;SI unit &lt;/strong&gt;is J/ (kg&amp;middot;K).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Heat gained by water = Heat lost by glass&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Heat gained/lost by the system&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;H = m c &amp;Delta;T, Where m = mass, c = specific heat capacity, &amp;Delta;T = temperature change.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CALCULATION:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given that: m&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 100 g, t&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 350&amp;deg;C, c&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = 0.8 J/g &amp;deg; C and m&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = 1 kg = 1000 g, t&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = 23.6&amp;deg;C, c&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = 4.0 J/g&amp;deg;C.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let the final temperature of the system will be x&amp;deg;C.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Heat lost by glass = Heat gained by water&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;m&lt;sub&gt;1 &lt;/sub&gt;c&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; (t&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;ndash; x) = m&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; c&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; (x &amp;ndash; t&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;100 &amp;times; 0.8 &amp;times; (350 &amp;ndash; x) = 1000 &amp;times; 4.0 (x &amp;ndash; 23.6)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;350 &amp;ndash; x = 50 (x &amp;ndash; 23.6)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;51 x = 1530 &amp;rArr; &lt;strong&gt;x = 30&amp;deg;C.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So option 3 is correct.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Power factor:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;The &lt;strong&gt;ratio of the true power&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;to the apparent power &lt;/strong&gt;of an a.c. the circuit is called the&lt;strong&gt; power factor.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Its &lt;strong&gt;value&lt;/strong&gt; varies &lt;strong&gt;from 0 to 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;power factor (p.f)&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;of a &lt;strong&gt;series LCR-circuit &lt;/strong&gt;is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Power factor (P)&lt;/strong&gt; = Cos&amp;nbsp;&amp;Phi;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\cos {\rm{Φ }} = \frac{R}{Z} = \frac{R}{{\sqrt {{R^2} + {{\left( {{X_L} - {X_C}} \right)}^2}} }}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where R = resistance, Z = Impedance, X&lt;sub&gt;L&lt;/sub&gt; = Inductive reactance and X&lt;sub&gt;C&lt;/sub&gt; = Capacitive reactance&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CALCULATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given that:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;R = 100 &amp;Omega;,&amp;nbsp; X&lt;sub&gt;L&lt;/sub&gt; = 200 &amp;Omega;, X&lt;sub&gt;c&lt;/sub&gt; = 100 &amp;Omega;, V = 220 V and &amp;nu; = 50 Hz&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;power factor&lt;/strong&gt; of a &lt;strong&gt;series LCR-circuit &lt;/strong&gt;is given by&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\cos {\rm{Φ }} = \frac{R}{{\sqrt {{R^2} + {{\left( {{X_L} - {X_C}} \right)}^2}} }}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( \Rightarrow {\rm{\;cosΦ }} = \frac{{100}}{{\sqrt {{{\left( {100} \right)}^2} + {{\left( {200 - 100} \right)}^2}} }} = \frac{{\;100}}{{100\sqrt 2 }} = \frac{1}{{\sqrt 2 }}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( \Rightarrow {\rm{Φ }} = {\cos ^{ - 1}}\left( {\frac{1}{{\sqrt 2 }}} \right) = 45^\circ \)&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span data-darkreader-inline-bgcolor=&quot;&quot; data-darkreader-inline-bgimage=&quot;&quot;&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span data-darkreader-inline-bgcolor=&quot;&quot; data-darkreader-inline-bgimage=&quot;&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Magnetic field (B):&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;The space or region around the&amp;nbsp;current-carrying&amp;nbsp;wire/moving electric charge&amp;nbsp;or around the magnetic material in which&amp;nbsp;force of magnetism&amp;nbsp;can be experienced by other magnetic material is called as&amp;nbsp;magnetic field/magnetic induction&amp;nbsp;by that material/current.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;magnetic force per unit length&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;between &lt;strong&gt;two parallel wires&lt;/strong&gt; is given by&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{F}{l} = \frac{{{\mu _o}}}{{2\pi }}\frac{{2{I_1}{I_2}}}{d}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where &amp;mu;&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;= permittivity of free space, I&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;= current in a first wire, I&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;= current in a second wire,d = distance between two wires, and l = length of current-carrying wire.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;magnetic force per unit length&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;between &lt;strong&gt;two parallel wires&lt;/strong&gt; is given by&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{F}{l} = \frac{{{\mu _o}}}{{4\pi }}\frac{{2{I_1}{I_2}}}{d}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;From the above, it is clear that the &lt;strong&gt;force &lt;/strong&gt;between the two parallel wires depends on the medium in which two-wire is placed, the distance between two-wire and the current in wire 1 and wire 2.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span data-darkreader-inline-bgcolor=&quot;&quot; data-darkreader-inline-bgimage=&quot;&quot;&gt;If the &lt;strong&gt;distance between two straight currents carrying wire is increased&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, then the &lt;strong&gt;force &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span data-darkreader-inline-bgcolor=&quot;&quot; data-darkreader-inline-bgimage=&quot;&quot;&gt;between them will decrease&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span data-darkreader-inline-bgcolor=&quot;&quot; data-darkreader-inline-bgimage=&quot;&quot;&gt;. Therefore, option 2 is correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/19/06/Railways_Solution%20Improvement_Satya_10%20June_Madhu%28Dia%29.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 140px; height: 43px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the conductor &lt;strong&gt;carries&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;current in the same direction&lt;/strong&gt;, then the &lt;strong&gt;force between them will be attractive&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the conductor &lt;strong&gt;carries current in the opposite direction&lt;/strong&gt;, then the &lt;strong&gt;force between them will be repulsive&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The material which is not a good conductor or a good insulator is called as&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;semiconductor&lt;/strong&gt;. For example: Silicon&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;charge carriers&amp;nbsp;which are present in more quantity in a semiconductor compared to other particles are called&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;majority charge carrier&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The semiconductor device which is used to control the flow of electric current is called as&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;p-n junction diode&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;p-n&amp;nbsp;Junction&amp;nbsp;diode has one p node and one n node&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the &lt;strong&gt;reverse bias, the negative voltage node is connected to p node&lt;/strong&gt;. That means the positive voltage node is connected to n node.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F1_J.K_29.5.20_Pallavi_D10.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this way, the &lt;strong&gt;width of the depletion layer increases due to lack of electrons and holes&lt;/strong&gt;. So &lt;strong&gt;reversed bias&lt;/strong&gt; means opposite of conventional connection with high diode width.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence the &lt;strong&gt;thickness of the depletion layer increase in reverse biasing&lt;/strong&gt;. So option 1 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Electromagnetic waves:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a transverse wave defined as &lt;strong&gt;composed of oscillating electrical and magnetic fields perpendicular to each other.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Speed of electromagnetic waves is the same as of &lt;strong&gt;speed of light c = 3 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;8&lt;/sup&gt; m/s&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(speed\;of\;EMW = \frac{1}{{\sqrt {{\epsilon_0}\;{\mu _0}} }} = 3 \times {10^8}\;m/s   \)&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;ϵ&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt; = 8.854 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;-12&lt;/sup&gt; F/m&lt;/strong&gt; (permittivity of free space).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;mu;&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt; = 4&amp;pi; &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;-7&lt;/sup&gt; H/m&lt;/strong&gt; ( permeability of free space).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;relation between&lt;/strong&gt; the &lt;strong&gt;speed of the electromagnetic wave and dielectric constant&lt;/strong&gt; and vacuum permeability:&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus the&lt;strong&gt; electromagnetic wave speed (c) &lt;/strong&gt;is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(c = \frac{1}{{\sqrt {{\epsilon_0}\;{\mu _0}} }}    \)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As the &lt;strong&gt;speed of the electromagnetic waves in a medium is inversely proportional to the permeability of the medium&lt;/strong&gt; then it will &lt;strong&gt;decrease by increasing the permeability of the medium&lt;/strong&gt;. So option 2 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Eddy Current&lt;/strong&gt;: When a&amp;nbsp;changing magnetic flux&amp;nbsp;is applied to a&amp;nbsp;bulk piece of conducting material&amp;nbsp;then&amp;nbsp;circulating currents&amp;nbsp;is called&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;eddy currents&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;are induced in the material.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Because the&amp;nbsp;resistance&lt;/strong&gt; of the bulk conductor&amp;nbsp;is usually&amp;nbsp;low,&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;eddy currents&amp;nbsp;often have&amp;nbsp;large magnitudes&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;heat the conductor.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Due to&lt;strong&gt; heating of the conductor there is a loss in energy. &lt;/strong&gt;This loss is called&lt;strong&gt; eddy current loss.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F1_J.K_29.5.20_Pallavi_D9.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;eddy current loss can be reduced by increasing the resistance of the core&lt;/strong&gt;. So option 1 is not correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;eddy current loss can be reduced by using a laminated core&lt;/strong&gt; like in the above diagram. So option 2 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Electric potential&lt;/strong&gt;: The amount of work done to move a unit charge particle from infinity to a point in an electric field is called as &lt;strong&gt;potential&lt;/strong&gt; at that point. The &lt;strong&gt;SI unit of electric potential is Volt (V).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;electric potential (V)&lt;/strong&gt; due to a charge particle at a distance x is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(V = \;\frac{{Kq}}{x}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The space or region around the&lt;strong&gt; electric charge&lt;/strong&gt; in which &lt;strong&gt;electrostatic force&lt;/strong&gt; can be experienced by other charge particle is called as &lt;strong&gt;electric field (E) &lt;/strong&gt;by that electric charge.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;electric Field (E)&lt;/strong&gt; due to a charge particle at a distance x is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(E = \frac{{Kq}}{{{x^2}}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where K is a constant = 9 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;9&lt;/sup&gt; Nm&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;/C&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;, q is charge and x is distance from charge particle.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;From the formula of electric potential (V) and electric field (E):&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;relationship between electric field and potential difference&lt;/strong&gt; is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(E = - \frac{{{\rm{d\;}}V}}{{{\rm{d\;}}x}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence option 3 is correct.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The&amp;nbsp;first&amp;nbsp;law&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;thermodynamics&amp;nbsp;is a restatement of the&amp;nbsp;law&amp;nbsp;of conservation of energy.&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;It states that energy cannot be created or destroyed in an isolated system; energy can only be transferred or changed from one form to another.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;According to the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;first&amp;nbsp;law&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;Thermodynamics&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;Delta;Q = &amp;Delta;W + &amp;Delta;U&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Second law of thermodynamics&lt;/strong&gt;: The entropy of an isolated system not in equilibrium will tend to increase over time, approaching a maximum value at equilibrium.

	&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In other words- The &lt;strong&gt;second&amp;nbsp;law&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;thermodynamics&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;states that the &lt;strong&gt;total entropy&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;an isolated system always increases over time&lt;/strong&gt;, or remains constant in ideal cases where the system is in a steady-state or undergoing a reversible process. This increase in entropy accounts for the irreversibility&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;natural processes.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Entropy&lt;/strong&gt; is a measure of disturbance, higher the&amp;nbsp;entropy&amp;nbsp;with the positive sign, more are the chances of the reaction taking place spontaneously. The SI unit of&amp;nbsp;Entropy is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Joule per Kelvin (J/K)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;second&amp;nbsp;law&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;gives the definition of &lt;strong&gt;entropy&lt;/strong&gt; term.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;Delta;S = &amp;Delta;Q/T&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where &amp;Delta; S is entropy change, &amp;Delta; Q is energy change and T is temperature&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;From the above discussion, we can say that the &lt;strong&gt;entropy is explained by the second law of thermodynamics&lt;/strong&gt;. So option 2 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ideal gas:&lt;/strong&gt; It is a hypothetical gas, consisting of molecules that are having &lt;strong&gt;negligible volume&lt;/strong&gt; and their &lt;strong&gt;collision is perfectly elastically&lt;/strong&gt; (means no loss of energy) and &lt;strong&gt;obeys gas law.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
The &lt;strong&gt;ideal gas equation&lt;/strong&gt; is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;P V = n R T&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where P= pressure of the gas, V = volume of the gas, n = moles of the gas, R = 8.314 J/mol-K (Universal gas constant), T = temperature of the gas.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There are specific cases for &lt;strong&gt;pressure constant&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;volume constant&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;temperature constants&lt;/strong&gt; :

	&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Boyle&amp;rsquo;s law/Isothermal process&lt;/strong&gt;: It allows to set up the &lt;strong&gt;relationship between the changes in pressure and volume&lt;/strong&gt; under &lt;strong&gt;constant temperature&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;P&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;V&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = P&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;V&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; so &lt;strong&gt;P V = Constant&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; [P&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; and P&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; are pressure of gases and V&lt;sub&gt;1 &lt;/sub&gt;and V&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; are volume]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Charles&amp;rsquo;s law/Isobaric process:&lt;/strong&gt; It allows to set up &lt;strong&gt;the relationship between the changes in volume and temperature&lt;/strong&gt; under &lt;strong&gt;constant pressure&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;V&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;/T&lt;sub&gt;1 &lt;/sub&gt;= V&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;/T&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; so &lt;strong&gt;V &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;prop; T&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; [V&lt;sub&gt;1 &lt;/sub&gt;and V&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; are volume and T&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; and T&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; are different temperatures]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Isochoric process&lt;/strong&gt;: The process in which the &lt;strong&gt;volume of the gas remains constant&lt;/strong&gt; is called isochoric process. &lt;strong&gt;For example&lt;/strong&gt;: A gas is filled in a closed container then volume of the gas will remain constant.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In an &lt;strong&gt;isochoric process:&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{P}{T} = Constant\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In case of &lt;strong&gt;isobaric process, the pressure remains constant&lt;/strong&gt;. From the above graph given, the &lt;strong&gt;presssure remains constant in graph BC&lt;/strong&gt; only. So &lt;strong&gt;BC shows the isobaric process&lt;/strong&gt;. Hence option 2 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Graph &lt;strong&gt;AB shows the isothermal process&lt;/strong&gt; becase temperature remains constant during AB. So option 1 is wrong.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Graph &lt;strong&gt;AC is some polytropic&lt;/strong&gt; curve. So option 3 is wrong.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Grouping of Cells:&lt;/strong&gt; In a series grouping of cell&amp;rsquo;s their emf&amp;rsquo;s are additive or subtractive while their internal resistances are always additive.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Series grouping:&lt;/strong&gt; In series grouping anode of one cell is connected to the cathode of other cells and so on.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F1_P.B_8.5.20_Pallavi_D7.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 174px; height: 133px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If &lt;strong&gt;n identical cells&lt;/strong&gt; are connected in &lt;strong&gt;series&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ol style=&quot;margin-left: 40px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Equivalent emf &lt;/strong&gt;of the combination&amp;nbsp; E&lt;sub&gt;eq&lt;/sub&gt; = &lt;strong&gt;nE&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Equivalent internal resistance&lt;/strong&gt; r&lt;sub&gt;eq&lt;/sub&gt; = &lt;strong&gt;nr&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CALCULATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given- emf of three cells = E&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = E&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = E&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = E and internal resistance = r&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = r&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = r&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = r&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Equivalent emf of the combination&amp;nbsp; is&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; E&lt;sub&gt;eq&lt;/sub&gt; = E&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; + E&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; + E&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = E + E + E = 3E&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Similarly,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Equivalent internal resistance&amp;nbsp; is&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; r&lt;sub&gt;eq&lt;/sub&gt; = r&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; + r&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; + r&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = r + r + r = 3r&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So option 3 is correct.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The device which is used to measure the heat for calorimetry is called a&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;calorimeter&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A calorimeter consists of a metallic vessel&lt;/strong&gt; made of materials that are &lt;strong&gt;good conductors of electricity&lt;/strong&gt; like copper and aluminum.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is used to measure the &lt;strong&gt;thermal changes&lt;/strong&gt; of a body.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F1_J.K_Madhu_21.05.20_D6.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;vessel of a calorimeter is made up of a metallic material because it is a good conductor of electricity&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Due to these good conducting materials, we can &lt;strong&gt;conduct electricity for giving heat via an electric heater.&lt;/strong&gt; So option 1 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pressure&lt;/strong&gt;: Pressure&amp;nbsp;is defined as the &lt;strong&gt;physical force exerted on an object. &lt;/strong&gt;The unit of&amp;nbsp;pressure&amp;nbsp;is &lt;strong&gt;Pascal&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The basic formula for&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;pressure&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;P = F/A, Where P is pressure, F = force, A = area.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The pressure exerted by &lt;strong&gt;a liquid on the wall of container&lt;/strong&gt; can be given by&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;P = &amp;rho; h g, Where &amp;rho; = density of liquid, h = height of the liquid, g = gravity.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/06/F1_J.K_29.6.20_Pallavi_D1.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 250px; height: 177px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;pressure exerted by a liquid on the wall of container&lt;/strong&gt; can be given by&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;P = &amp;rho; h g, Where &amp;rho; = density of liquid, h = height of the liquid, g = gravity.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus it &lt;strong&gt;depends on the density of the liquid, height of the liquid in the container, and the acceleration due to gravity&lt;/strong&gt;. So option 4 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Simple Harmonic Motion (SHM): &lt;/strong&gt;Simple harmonic motion is a &lt;strong&gt;special&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;type&lt;/strong&gt; of &lt;strong&gt;periodic&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;motion&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;oscillation&lt;/strong&gt; where the &lt;strong&gt;restoring&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;force&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;directly&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;proportional&lt;/strong&gt; to the &lt;strong&gt;displacement&lt;/strong&gt; and acts in the &lt;strong&gt;direction&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;opposite&lt;/strong&gt; to that of &lt;strong&gt;displacement.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;Motion of an undamped pendulum, undamped spring-mass system&lt;strong&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;equation of shm&lt;/strong&gt; is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Y = A Sin (&amp;omega; t + &amp;theta;)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where A is amplitude, &amp;omega; is angular frequency, t is time, &amp;theta; is initial phase angle and y is displacement from mean position.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given that: y = A Sin (4&amp;pi; t)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Time (t) = 1/24 sec&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;y = A Sin (4&amp;pi; t) = A Sin (4&amp;pi; &amp;times; 1/24) = A Sin (&amp;pi;/6) = A/2&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Displacement from the nearby extreme&lt;/strong&gt; = A &amp;ndash; y = A &amp;ndash; A/2 = A/2

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rolling motion: &lt;/strong&gt;Rolling motion can be regarded as a combination of &lt;strong&gt;pure rotation and pure translation&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When an &lt;strong&gt;object&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;rolling on a plane without slipping&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;the point of contact of the object with the plane does not move&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;rolling object&amp;#39;s velocity&lt;/strong&gt; v is directly related to its &lt;strong&gt;angular velocity &amp;omega;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mathematically it is expressed as V = &amp;omega;R&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where R = the object&amp;#39;s radius and V = its linear velocity.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F1_P.Y_Madhu_13.05.20_D%204.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 176px; height: 151px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In pure rolling motion, the point of contact (bottom-most point) moves with velocity&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;V&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt; = velocity of point P = V&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; V&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt; = (V&amp;rsquo; - &amp;omega;R) = V&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; &lt;strong&gt;V&amp;rsquo; = V&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt; + &amp;omega;R&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where V&amp;rsquo; = linear velocity of solid sphere&lt;/p&gt;
V = velocity of planck

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Elements of Earth&amp;#39;s Magnetic Field: &lt;/strong&gt;The magnitude and direction of the magnetic field of the earth at a place are completely given by certain quantities known as magnetic elements.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Magnetic Declination (&amp;theta;)&lt;/strong&gt;: It is the angle between&amp;nbsp;geographic and the magnetic meridian planes.
	&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type:circle;&quot;&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Declination&amp;nbsp;at a place is expressed at&amp;nbsp;&amp;theta;&amp;deg; E or &amp;theta;&amp;deg; W&amp;nbsp;depending upon whether the north pole of the compass needle lies to the east or to the west of the geographical axis.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The angle of inclination or Dip (&amp;Phi;&lt;/strong&gt;): It is the angle between the&amp;nbsp;direction of the intensity of the total magnetic field&amp;nbsp;of earth and a&amp;nbsp;horizontal line in the magnetic meridian.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/04/F1_Prabhu_Deepak_27.03.2020_D3.png&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/Physics%20ST%201_Group%20X_Jitendra_Sunny_15.5.2020%206.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 403px; height: 246px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;horizontal component (B&lt;sub&gt;H&lt;/sub&gt;) is&amp;nbsp;B&lt;sub&gt;H&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;= B cos &amp;Phi;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The vertical component (B&lt;sub&gt;V&lt;/sub&gt;) is&amp;nbsp;B&lt;sub&gt;V&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;= B sin &amp;Phi;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where B&lt;sub&gt;V &lt;/sub&gt;is vertical component of magnetic field, B&lt;sub&gt;H&lt;/sub&gt; is horizontal component of magnetic field, B is net magnetic field of earth and &amp;Phi; is angle of dip.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given that: Angle of dip (&amp;Phi;) = 60&amp;deg; and horizontal component of magnetic field (B&lt;sub&gt;H&lt;/sub&gt;) = 24 T&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;horizontal component (B&lt;sub&gt;H&lt;/sub&gt;) is&amp;nbsp;B&lt;sub&gt;H&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;= B cos &amp;Phi;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;24 = B &amp;times; Cos 60&amp;deg; = B/2&lt;/p&gt;
Net Magnetic field of earth (B) = 24 &amp;times; 2 = 48 T

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Eddy Current:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;When a changing magnetic flux is applied to a bulk piece of conducting material then circulating currents is called eddy currents are induced in the material.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Because the &lt;strong&gt;resistance of the bulk conductor&lt;/strong&gt; is usually &lt;strong&gt;low&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;eddy currents&lt;/strong&gt; often have &lt;strong&gt;large magnitudes &lt;/strong&gt;and &lt;strong&gt;heat the conductor&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Eddy currents&lt;/strong&gt; are the currents induced in solid metallic masses when magnetic flux threading through them changes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Eddy current&lt;/strong&gt; is also known as&lt;strong&gt;&amp;ldquo;Focault current&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Eddy current&lt;/strong&gt; also &lt;strong&gt;opposes the change in magnetic flux&lt;/strong&gt;, so there is given by &lt;strong&gt;Lenz&amp;rsquo;s law&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Total&amp;nbsp;internal&amp;nbsp;reflection&amp;nbsp;(TIR):&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;It&amp;nbsp;occurs at the interface of two transparent medium when the ray of light travels from a denser medium to a rarer medium.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;critical angle&lt;/strong&gt; is the angle of &lt;strong&gt;incidence&lt;/strong&gt; in the denser medium for which &lt;strong&gt;the angle of refraction&lt;/strong&gt; in the &lt;strong&gt;rarer medium&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;90&amp;deg;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Total&amp;nbsp;internal&amp;nbsp;reflection&amp;nbsp;(TIR)&lt;/strong&gt; of light is the&amp;nbsp;reflection&amp;nbsp;of light &lt;strong&gt;within the same medium&lt;/strong&gt; when a ray of light is incident&amp;nbsp;at the interface of two medium at an &lt;strong&gt;angle of incidence which is greater than the critical angle&lt;/strong&gt; for the pair of media i.e. &lt;strong&gt;i &amp;gt;i&lt;sub&gt;c&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The relation between &lt;strong&gt;refractive index&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;critical angle&lt;/strong&gt; is&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\mu = \frac{1}{{\sin C}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CALCULATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given - &amp;mu;&lt;sub&gt;g&lt;/sub&gt; = 3/2 and &amp;mu;&lt;sub&gt;w&lt;/sub&gt; = 4/3&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The relation between &lt;strong&gt;refractive index&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;critical angle&lt;/strong&gt; is&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\mu _g^w = \frac{{{\mu _g}}}{{{\mu _w}}} = \frac{1}{{\sin C}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\Rightarrow C = {\sin ^{ - 1}}\left( {\frac{{{\mu _w}}}{{{\mu _g}}}} \right) = {\sin ^{ - 1}}\left( {\frac{{\frac{4}{3}}}{{\frac{3}{2}}}} \right) = {\sin ^{ - 1}}\left( {\frac{8}{9}} \right)\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So option 3 is correct.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Self-Induction:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;Whenever the electric &lt;strong&gt;current passing through a coil changes&lt;/strong&gt;, the &lt;strong&gt;magnetic flux linked with it will also change&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to &lt;strong&gt;Faraday&amp;rsquo;s laws of electromagnetic induction&lt;/strong&gt;, an &lt;strong&gt;emf is induced in the coil&lt;/strong&gt; which &lt;strong&gt;opposes the change that causes it&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This phenomenon is called &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;self-induction&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo; and the emf induced is called &lt;strong&gt;back emf&lt;/strong&gt;, current so produced in the coil is called &lt;strong&gt;induced current&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Self-inductance of a solenoid&lt;/strong&gt; is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(L = \frac{{{\mu _o}{N^2}A}}{l}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where &amp;mu;&lt;sub&gt;o&lt;/sub&gt; = Absolute permeability, N = Number of turns, l = length of the solenoid and A = Area of the solenoid.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Self-inductance of a solenoid is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(L = \frac{{{\mu _o}{N^2}A}}{l}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;From the above equation, it is clear that the &lt;strong&gt;self-induction of a solenoid is directly proportional to the number of turns&lt;/strong&gt; of the solenoid. Thus option 4 is correct and option 1 is incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;self-induction of a solenoid is inversely proportional to its length&lt;/strong&gt;. Thus option 2 is incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;self-induction of a solenoid is directly proportional to the area of cross-section&lt;/strong&gt;. Thus option 3 is incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;An &lt;strong&gt;echo&lt;/strong&gt; is simply the repetition of a speaker&amp;#39;s own voice caused by &lt;strong&gt;reflection&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;at a distance surface&lt;/strong&gt; e.g. a cliff, a row of the building, or any other extended surface.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Frequency can be divided into three categories based on their frequency range:&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Audible sound&amp;nbsp;waves:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;The &lt;strong&gt;frequency range&lt;/strong&gt; of this&amp;nbsp;wave&amp;nbsp;is &lt;strong&gt;20Hz - 20000Hz&lt;/strong&gt;. Humans can easily detect these types of&amp;nbsp;waves.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Example: Sound produced by Vocal cords.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Infrasonic&amp;nbsp;waves:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;The &lt;strong&gt;frequency range &lt;/strong&gt;of these types of&amp;nbsp;a wave&amp;nbsp;is &lt;strong&gt;below 20Hz&lt;/strong&gt;. Humans cannot detect it.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Example: Sound produced by &lt;strong&gt;Earthquake&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Volcanic eruption&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;ocean&amp;nbsp;waves,&lt;/strong&gt; etc.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ultrasonic&amp;nbsp;waves or Ultrasound&amp;nbsp;waves:&lt;/strong&gt; The sound &lt;strong&gt;frequency above 20,000 Hz &lt;/strong&gt;is known as &lt;strong&gt;ultrasonic&amp;nbsp;waves&lt;/strong&gt;. Humans cannot detect it too.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Examples: Dog whistle is an example of an Ultrasound&amp;nbsp;wave.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The types of sound&amp;nbsp;waves&amp;nbsp;whose frequencies are higher than the upper audible limit of human hearing are called &lt;strong&gt;ultrasound&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bats&lt;/strong&gt; produce &lt;strong&gt;ultrasonic&amp;nbsp;waves&lt;/strong&gt; whose &lt;strong&gt;frequency range is above 20,000Hz&lt;/strong&gt;. Therefore option 2 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/19/06/Railways_Solution%20Improvement_Satya_10%20June_Madhu%28Dia%29.png&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/Sectional%20test-2_Prabhu_Sunny_15.5.2020%201.PNG&quot; style=&quot;width: 181px; height: 59px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bats can&amp;rsquo;t create&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;waves like infrared, &lt;strong&gt;radio&amp;nbsp;waves,&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;electromagnetic&amp;nbsp;waves&lt;/strong&gt; and they &lt;strong&gt;can&amp;rsquo;t detect it too&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Viscous force (F)&lt;/strong&gt;: When a layer of fluid slips or tends to slip on adjacent layers in contact, the two layers exert tangential force on each other which tries to destroy the relative motion between them.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The property of a fluid due to which it opposes the relative motion between its different layers is called viscosity (or fluid friction or internal friction) and the force between the layers opposing the relative motion is called &lt;strong&gt;viscous force&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;force&lt;/strong&gt; acting between the &lt;strong&gt;different layers of a fluid&lt;/strong&gt; is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(F = - \eta A\frac{{dv}}{{dx}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where &amp;eta; = coefficient of viscosity, A = area of the plane and dv/dx = velocity gradient.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;margin-left: 40px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;negative sign&lt;/strong&gt; is employed because &lt;strong&gt;viscous force&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;acts&lt;/strong&gt; in a &lt;strong&gt;direction opposite to the flow of liquid&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The SI unit of viscosity is poiseiulle (Pl). Its other units are &lt;strong&gt;Nsm&lt;sup&gt;-2&lt;/sup&gt; or Pa s&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;force&lt;/strong&gt; acting between the &lt;strong&gt;different layers of a fluid&lt;/strong&gt; is given by &amp;ndash;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(F = - \eta A\frac{{dv}}{{dx}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;From the above formula, it is clear that the &lt;strong&gt;viscous force&lt;/strong&gt; depends on the &lt;strong&gt;area of the layer of fluid &lt;/strong&gt;i.e. if &lt;strong&gt;surface area increases&lt;/strong&gt; then the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;viscous force&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;will also &lt;strong&gt;increase&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F2_P.Y_Madhu_11.05.20_D1.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 251px; height: 179px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/19/06/Railways_Solution%20Improvement_Satya_10%20June_Madhu%28Dia%29.png&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/Sectional%20test-2_Prabhu_Sunny_15.5.2020%201.PNG&quot; style=&quot;width: 181px; height: 59px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;With an &lt;strong&gt;increase in pressure&lt;/strong&gt;, the &lt;strong&gt;viscosity of liquids (except water) increases&lt;/strong&gt; while that of gases is practically independent of pressure. The viscosity of water decreases with an increase in pressure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;viscosity of liquid decreases&lt;/strong&gt; with an &lt;strong&gt;increase of temperature&lt;/strong&gt;, because the cohesive force between the liquid molecules decreases with an increase of temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The idealized heat engine is one that is operated in a reversible manner or engine that follows &lt;strong&gt;Carnot cycle&lt;/strong&gt; and has no internal friction and inefficiencies but those that are fundamental.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;No heat engine can have an efficiency greater than a reversible heat engine.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;All Reversible Heat Engines have the same efficiency when operating between the same two temperature reservoirs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence as explained above an &lt;strong&gt;ideal heat engine is the one which follows Carnot cycle&lt;/strong&gt;, i.e., the &lt;strong&gt;efficiency of heat engine cannot be great then 1&lt;/strong&gt; (Property of Carnot engine)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Also, and ideal heat engine cannot be irreversible&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, only option 2 is correct among all&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;An&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;electromagnet&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is a type of magnet in which the magnetic field is produced by an electric current.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;magnetic field disappears&lt;/strong&gt; when the current is turned off.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When a &lt;strong&gt;soft&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;iron core&lt;/strong&gt; is inserted inside the solenoid then the strength of the&lt;strong&gt; magnetic&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;field&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;becomes&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;very large &lt;/strong&gt;because&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;the iron core gets magnetized by induction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;soft iron core&lt;/strong&gt; helps in concentrating the magnetic lines of forces through the solenoid so that the magnetic field is almost uniform at the end face of the core.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, the &lt;strong&gt;strength of the magnetic&amp;nbsp;field&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;increases&lt;/strong&gt; when a &lt;strong&gt;soft iron&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;core&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;inserted inside a solenoid&lt;/strong&gt;. Therefore, option 1 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/19/06/Railways_Solution%20Improvement_Satya_10%20June_Madhu%28Dia%29.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 180px; height: 55px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;strength&amp;nbsp;of an&amp;nbsp;electromagnet&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;can be &lt;strong&gt;increased&lt;/strong&gt; by &lt;strong&gt;increasing the number of turns of wire&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;around the&amp;nbsp;iron core&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;and by &lt;strong&gt;increasing the current or voltage&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;CONCEPT:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Total&amp;nbsp;internal&amp;nbsp;reflection&amp;nbsp;(TIR):&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Total&amp;nbsp;internal&amp;nbsp;reflection&amp;nbsp;(TIR)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;occurs at the interface of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;two transparent medium&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;when the ray of light travels from a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;denser medium to a rarer medium&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;critical angle&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the angle of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;incidence&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in the denser medium for which&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;the angle of refraction&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;rarer medium&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;90&amp;deg;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Total&amp;nbsp;internal&amp;nbsp;reflection&amp;nbsp;(TIR)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of light is the&amp;nbsp;reflection&amp;nbsp;of light&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;within the same medium&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;when a ray of light is incident&amp;nbsp;at the interface of two medium at an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;angle of incidence which is greater than the critical angle&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;for the pair of media i.e.&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;i &amp;gt;i&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;&quot;&gt;c&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Diamonds&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are known for their&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;spectacular brilliance&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;total internal reflection&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of light inside the diamond is the main reason for their brilliance. Therefore option 3 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;For the Diamond-Air interface, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;critical angle&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is (&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;@ 24.4&amp;deg;&lt;/span&gt;), which is&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;very small&lt;/span&gt;, therefore it is very likely to undergo total internal reflection inside it, once light enters a diamond.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Naturally found diamonds&amp;nbsp;rarely exhibit the brilliance for which they are known.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;technical skill&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;of a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;diamond cutter&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;makes&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;diamonds sparkle&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;so brilliantly.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;This is done by cutting&amp;nbsp;the diamond in different angles suitably, to make sure total internal reflections occur.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
